title: Uniformly perforated objects: a useful drainstrainer example

description.text:
I needed a drain-strainer for a 57mm drain hole that would not clog in a laundry trough that can experience large water inflows - with fluff that blocks standard drain-strainers.  
Not sure of the profile of the strainer that would yield best results - I wrote a small Rhino/Grasshopper model that takes an arbitary revolution profile and uniformly pierces it.   
The result performs very well - and there is now a computational geometry model that can create uniformly spaced perforations in an arbitrary revolved solid, which is useful of itself...

The downloadable files include:
  • printable STL
  • Rhino3D model
  • Grasshopper computational geometry model for production of a uniformly perforated revolved solid from an abritrary profile
  • STEP model (no parametric capability)
    • The model files will allow you to scale this for any sized plug hole. If you use Rhino3D, you will find the Grasshopper file very useful for generating uniformly spaced perforations in any revolved solid. All the parameters to adjust spacings, wall widths and piercing scales are in the GH model. You could substitute any arbitrary closed curve for the circle I used to create very complex piercings if you like!

comments.text: Nicely done.  I'm more interested in the hole pattern generator than the profile though.
comments.author: Makezilla

comments.text: If you download the model you will find the Grasshopper script that delivers uniform perforations with any "cutter" (does not need to be a circle) on any rotated surface...

title: LED mounts for Wanhao i3 / other frames?

description.text:
These mounts clamp on the aluminium frame of the Wanhao i3 (Plus in my case) and house standard 5mm LEDs. The connections are hidden behind a cover which clicks neatly in place. A similar mount for a round DC jack is included.

I connected all the pieces using Dupont connectors and some ribbon cable. The LEDs I use are white 3V, each set of 4 in series to run off a 12V power supply. I've added a 10 ohm resistor to each set.

All the dimensions are in variables so it should be easy to change for example the clamp to match an acrylic frame. The amount of LEDs and where they point are in a vector as well.

Update: I've added a mount for the top to house another 4 LEDs. It doesn't add much to the visibility on the build plate itself, but looks good nonetheless. I also rotated all the parts to their preferred printing orientation.

description.text:
Working with a group of friends we decided to build a NeoPixel Camera mounted Light Ring utilizing inexpensive parts. We wanted something that was on the verge of plug-n-play without complicated programming and wiring connections. This is the result of that endeavor. With a couple of purchased items and a day or so of printing you can have a light ring for you photography, that not only lights up but also can change color and increase and decrease in brightness.

This is still being tweaked and toyed with so like all my designs please be kind with comments and suggestions and check back for updated files with the changes.

What is needed:

1 of each printed part, except the box. You can choose to print the box either with or without a remote location.

2 - 3m x 25mm bolt
2 - 3m nuts

You will also need to purchase the following electronics:
http://www.ebay.com/itm/4X-RGB-90mm-5050-SMD-Headlight-Multi-Color-LED-Halo-Ring-Light-Kit-Angel-Eye-12V-/272183292852

http://www.ebay.com/itm/USB-DC-5V-to-12V-Step-up-Converter-Power-Supply-Charge-Cable-DC-2-1x5-5mm-Jack-/271939080469

http://www.ebay.com/itm/18650-Battery-Mobile-Power-Bank-Charger-Box-For-Phone-Tablet-LED-5V-1A-USB-/161993535286?hash=item25b7912f36%3Ag%3AJTMAAOSw~gRVi8Jj

Printer Brand:

LulzBot

Printer:

TAZ 6

Yes

Supports:

Yes

.2 -.3

Infill:

20-50%

Notes:

You will need supports on the Box, and I like to use brims on everything else. Print the Arm in an upright position. The diffusor will need to be printed in either clear or a translucent material.

You will need to remove the support from the box print and then file and smooth the any left-over material the support may have left. The Arm will need to slid into this channel and the tolerances are tight. Carefully drill out the holes on the Arm, Hinge, Diffusor, and Ring Mount so that the 3m bolts can fit through. Also check these parts for fitment between their hinges, file or sand any issues you discover.

description.text:
This is a remix of http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1969059
Great idea and makes you printer look even more awesome! I made this remix because I prefer screws and nuts over snap fit joints. I used Tinkercad to combine the original endcap STL file (V1) and a screw I designed in OpenSCAD. Use two countersunk M4 x 8 mm screws and two hammer T-nuts per endcap to mount this version of the endcap.

Using these hands is an easy way to combine the Ikea Kallax 'play clock' door with the 'Rusch' clock to give you a functional clock in the Kallax format.

There are other ways, but by default the mechanism on the Rusch clock isn't long enough to poke through the thickness of the Kallax door.

Door: http://www.ikea.com/gb/en/products/storage-furniture/shelving-units-systems/kallax-insert-with-door-light-green-clock-decoration-art-30305820/
Clock: http://www.ikea.com/gb/en/products/decoration/clocks/rusch-wall-clock-white-art-70098989/

  1. Remove the default hands from the Rusch clock, separate the mechanism from the back of the clock face.
  2. Drill an 8mm hole in place of the standard hole in the Kallax clock door face.
  3. Line up the clock mechanism and push the new/printed hour hand through first (it's a push fit onto the mechansim).
  4. Wind the hour hand to the 12 O'clock position using the dial on the mechanism.
  5. Push the new/printed minute hand on next, also aligned to midnight.
  6. Set the time correctly using the dial on the mechanism, then add a battery.

Now I've designed a mailbox which hosts a 5mm led. To keep it simple, I'm using the Dupond cable terminators as led base.

  • Glue the flag to the side on the mailbox (I used Super Glue with PLA)

description.text:
I was using kennethjiang's tensioner, not at what I thought was excessively high tension, and it popped on me (see picture). It opened like a french door, letting the nut pull straight through. I found LittleMrJ's remix, but it didn't seem to do anything about putting more material where mine broke. So I came up with this remix, which expands on LittleMrJ's version of removing the forward channel, by adding lobes which both center the tension rod through the gap in the bracket and adds more material to try to avoid the failure of the first part.

I printed as shown in the stl with base support and a wide (20-line) brim, perhaps it could also be flipped 180 degrees to print the fork at the bottom.

Tinkercad: https://tinkercad.com/things/k4HlKgzgjWB

Update 2017-01-28: This part failed on me in a different way, see my remix: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2069419

I'd really advise against making this part, relying on the layer adhesion is a serious weakness in this design. Please consider the remix^3 above, which is still working well for me.

title: Revolver themed AAA battery storage container (parametric)

description.text:
This is a container that holds 6 cylindrical batteries (set to AAA size right now, but adjustable).

Still untested at the moment.
Update:
2017-02-02: Added clearance to the holes -- batteries can go in and out of the container easily now. Ratcheting mechanism needs to be tweaked to allow for a larger, stronger spring.

Assembly
  1. Print the body and cap pieces
  2. Insert an M3 nylock nut into the nut trap underneath the body piece and push it all the way in.
  3. Stick an M3 cap screw through the cap piece
  4. Insert springs (2mm OD, in the current design, but adjustable) into the 3 little holes at the top of the cap piece.
  5. Put a ball bearing on top of each spring (4mm OD).
  6. Install the cap piece and secure it with the cap screw.

If done properly, it should allow you to turn the cap piece relative to the body, snapping into 12 stable locations. 6 of them correspond to each of the battery holes, and the other 6 are in between, which should keep all 6 batteries from falling out.

title: Carriage Rest for Geeetech Rostock G2S printer

description.text:
Carriage Rest for Geeetech Rostock G2S

This is a simple but effective modification for the Geeetech Rostock G2S printer. The printable part is a rest for the carriage which clips to the set of guide rails at the back of the printer.

In conjunction with some custom g-code which is simply added to the "post printing g-code" section of your slicer, the carriage can be made to return to its home position, then move towards the back of the machine, and come down to gently sit on the carriage rest. The stepper motors can then be disabled, and the carriage wont come crashing down on your freshly completed item. This can be used instead of the more traditional carriage clip, which I personally never found to be terribly successful.

The carriage rest should be positioned approximately 13cm above the lower frame panel of the printer (i.e. the bit that the bed sits on), so that the sliding section on that guide rail can still move low enough for the carriage to reach to the front of the bed at its lowest point. In that position, the carriage will sit neatly on the rest when the custom g-code is sent to the printer. When you fit the carriage rest in place, you will need to send the g-code to the printer, and then adjust its height to position it precisely in place.

EDIT (1/2/2017): Added Version 2 of the carriage rest, which is designed to have greater stability.

title: Ducted fan modification for Geeetech Rostock G2S printer

description.text:
Ducted Fan Modification for Geeetech Rostock G2S

This is a modification for the Geeetech Rostock G2S printer. The printable parts assemble to form a ducted fan enclosure and nozzle for the carriage mounted cooling fan.

The factory fitted fan mount tends to just blow a weak stream of air in the general direction of the printed part, whereas better print results can often be obtained if the fan cools the freshly printed hot filament as soon as it is extruded. This modification encloses the standard 30mm fan in a box, and then directs the stream of air along a tube and through a flat duct near the print head. This has been proven to be very effective when printing small areas where the printing time per layer is very short.

The enclosure has been designed to hold the fan securely without the need for any mounting bolts. The enclosure and duct fit onto the original Geeetech G2S carriage, and uses the same mounting hardware that was supplied with the printer. The fan nozzle is a separate small part allowing it to be quickly and cheaply re-printed if it ever becomes damaged. There is a lid for the fan enclosure which is designed to be a tight press fit, and it has cable entry slots for the fan.

description.text: I designed this little bracket to hold a fiberglass rod that functions as an arch support for the bug mesh on my custom bridge hammock. (just like a tent pole on any standard dome tent but smaller and lighter) bridge hammocks function a bit differently from an end gathered hammock, if your a curious hiker it is worth a bit of googleing. This was designed to clip on to a .625 spreader pole and fits fairly snugly. This clip is used with the poles and titanium bridge clips that I bought from dutchwaregear.com. Dutch has all the neatest lightweight gear for backpacking and hammock suspension. If you are a D.I.Y junkie like me, this site is a great resource for all kinds of projects.

Notes:

The print setting are pretty basic. You should use a filament like abs or nylon that is strong and will hold up to heat better than pla. I printed this without support and my prusa handled the overhang pretty well. The socket for the fiberglass rod is inverted (if you print this in its native orientation) and there was a little distortion in the part here. However, this was just cosmetic and I ended up dressing the socket hole up with a small drill bit. The part works very well as designed.

I also expected that the fiberglass rod, when bent into position, would have pushed the clips around on the poles so I designed the clip with a recess and a guide that you should lace a bit of twine through (mine is the yellow twine in the pictures above). this will also insure that the clips are installed on the bar the same distance apart each time you set up. Thus your arches will be the same shape each time and you will have a better fit to the bug mesh.

title: Complete Graph K7 Embedded on a 3D Torus

description.text:
K7 is the complete graph on 7 vertices. You start with 7 vertices, and connect every pair with an edge, leading to 21 edges. It is not a planar graph, meaning it is impossible to draw K7 in the plane without having some edges cross. However, it is possible to embed the graph on a torus and not have any edges intersect. This design demonstrates this idea.

This object was designed by my research student, Zachary Ash, at Grand Valley State University. A companion object which demonstrates the embedding when the torus is drawn on the plane, is here: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1625128

The printed torus in the photograph was created by Shapeways, for about $20.

For mounting cameras - to avoid the yellow effect - a damper is required between the camera mount and the payload bridge. Additionally, I recommend to secure the camera mount with the bride with 2 cable binders through the central hole.

Besides the printed part you need to purchase the 1/4" screws and the dampers.
You can find them here:
Screws: https://www.amazon.de/MENGS-Schraube-Edelstahl-Einbeinstativ-Schnellwechselplatte/dp/B00IXDECV4/ref=pd_sim_421_5?_encoding=UTF8&psc=1&refRID=1GJV2T2Q8TTXAMB66AWT

For the dampers the hole size should be 7 mm.

As my first mounting plate was not long enough (too much drone in the video, see attached video) I extended the drone mount in the attached STL file.

I printed all parts in PET (white) or t-glase (silver grey) at 100 %.

Support

If you would like to support future free releases, please feel free to leave a tip (especially if you sell prints of my designs). I really want to keep on giving these things away for free.

Making use of the affiliate links that I provide to purchase parts is also a way of supporting me that doesn't cost you anything. I don't recommend anything that I haven't personally used.

Failing all of that, I heartily appreciate a credit or link back to my facebook page when you post your prints on social media.

Introduction

This is a an almost 100% 3D printed trailer for your 1:10 scale 4x4, based closely on the M416 trailer (it goes perfectly behind my jeep).

It includes working leaf-spring suspension, which I recommend printing in PETG

Video

https://youtu.be/FmGmvtKJsiY

Parts

Besides the printed parts you will need:

  • M2x5 (20)
  • M3x40 (1)
  • M2x10 (24)
  • M2x16 (6)
  • M3x12 (2)
  • M3 nuts (3)
  • M2 nuts (50)
  • M5 threaded rod (~160mm)

For each wheel you will need:

  • 1.9 Tyre (these go well with the Jeep)
  • M2x10 Screws (5)
  • M2 nuts (5)

Printer

All of the thin parts are designed in multiples of 0.4 for easy thin-wall printing with a 0.4mm nozzle.

description.text: This is loosely based on falcon20cne 's pen, pencil, tool holder which is a really great Thing ( http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:39632 and it certainly deserves more than 14 likes and I should know cause I won 1st place in the International Pen Pencil Holder Cool Thing Judge Symposium back in '06 ) Anyway, enough about that and more about this thing. Did I mention it's a Pen/Pencil/Tool holder but you have the option of adding your name? Of course, adding your name is for the benefit of anyone who walks into your cube/office/personal space and isn't sure if they walked into the right place. Certainly it's not for you cause I'm assuming you already know your name and don't need a daily reminder of what your name is. Altho, you could just print one for your friend and then print it with your name so your friend will always know it was you who gave it to him/her ... but that's probably got some downside to it but for the life of me I'm not sure I'm seeing it. It is NOT, I repeat NOT and under no uncertain terms, for your mother-in-law. Doing something nice for her will just encourage her and send the wrong signal. ( Never send a signal to your mother-in-law, wrong or otherwise, unless it's accompanied by a minimum of 60Hz. ) anyway, print, assemble and enjoy.

print the base as-is using your favorite color  
Load a copy of sketchup on your computer and start it.  
open the name.skp file and then select Tools, 3d Text.  
Input the name you want and select the font. I used script font.  
add the text to the drawing and scale it down such that it fits the long bar. If it fits the bar it will fit the holder. Make sure the bottom of the name and the long bar are touching so they print as one unit.  
add the name plate to the channel printed in the holder. I connected the name plate using some acetone.

The stack is mounted to the mid-plate, the four screws can be accessed when everything is completed. You can also use any other flightcontroller (F3, F4) that supports 30.5x30.5mm-mounting.

The arms are fixed with 12mm or 16mm M3-Screws and locknuts, you need 16 of them. The PDB and FC are mounted with 30,5x30,5mm schema with M3-Screws. You need 4 10mm-M3 to fix the first Level Nylon-Spacer or 4 30mm-M3-Screws if you wan't to use my CC3D-stack.

You can use 5" or 6"-props, any small battery around 1000mAh to 2200mAh will be fine. I use http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1905550 as motor-protector.

title: [RobotGeek V.2] BeefyArm - Robot Arm Mod (2017 Science Olympiad)

description.text:
This is a very simple, in line, Robot Arm extenders that fit onto the RobotGeek's V.2 Robotic Arm for the 2017 division C Science Olympiad. It should be fully rules complaint but check dimensions before using this design.

The BeefyArm will adds 20 cm of length to each segment of the robot it is attached to (40 cm as pictured). These parts require no modifications to the robot's frame and only requires 16 additional M2x10 bolts and nuts. Servo wiring extensions may be required.

Design Project: Project Apollo

====================================================================

Printed Parts needed:

4x RobotGeek BeefyArm

====================================================================

Hardware Needed:

16x M2x10 Bolts https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B00O9Y3ATG/

16x M2 nuts https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B00BG8TFR4/

====================================================================

Info on the Design:

The BeefyArm is a complete rethink of the ArmLong design. The Armlong is overly conservative and as such is extremely heavy for the minor loads it has to handle. With the BeefyArm the overall plan was to cut the fat and maximize the print length for my printer (a Rep1). Even though the BeefyArm is over twice the length of the ArmLong, 20 cm and 9.5 cm respectively, the overall increase in mass is minimal. I purchased a used rowing machine some years ago (15+) that only had one handle. It ended up being a real pain. Years before 3d printings arrival, I pieced together some pvc and solid plastic that did make using the rowing machine easier.

description.text:
I saw this Hand Spinner fidget toy online and decided to make one as well:

https://imgur.com/gallery/y3WcN

With my 3D printer and an old pair of inline skates, I was done in under 2 hours. It is a great idea, feels good in your hand and will give your hands something to fidget with.

Besides this print you will need to get 3 "608 ZZ" skate/skate board wheel bearings. The ZZ means that it has a metal shield on both sides for a nice and clean look. Amazon and EBay have plenty of these bearings for sale.

If you're thinking of making this, please read the details in Print Settings.

Notes:

This is a press-fit part, which means that getting the hole diameter correct is important. For my Ultimaker a 22.3mm hole diameter worked great for 22mm wholes. Your printer will work differently, so you may want to consider cloning this project in OnShape and adjusting the diameter according for your printer:

https://cad.onshape.com/documents/ac3353483a5068b0d7c9149c/w/53b8ceef1f5184844d8f5bc0/e/c7b1286eee8bb80ef7713004

Assembly

Once you're done with the print, clean up the foot on the bottom layer and use some find grit sand paper to make the inner wall nice and smooth. Once it feels close, but doesn't freely slide, put a bearing on the table and then press the printed part on the bearing.

If the bearing doesn't want to slip in, sand some more!

Use OnShape

I love the online CAD package OnShape -- it is easy to learn, super powerful and free for anyone making public documents. Great for makers! You can clone my project and modify it for your own use:

title: Simple 50mm part cooling fan for wanhao i3/ alike

description.text:
A 50mm axial blower/fan is probably the best alternative you can get for your 3D Printer and i can only recommend the upgrade if you are still running on the standard issue 30mm fan (or even on a 40mm fan).

There are some fancy all surround part cooler designs for the i3 out there, but i ran into lots of trouble with at least two of them. The cooler ring would eventually sag down a little, and the tight tolerances would case it to push over your print. Also i had my well isolated extruder block melt a large hole in my last fan-duct.

This one is kept simpler, yet very effective, and i was not able to make out a difference by directly comparing prints from this with a print from my previous toric fan-duct.

Lastly the engagement angle of the fan output is 40° which should be a lot more efficient than a 90° bend and the fan muzzle is as close to the hotend as i dared to.

Wanhao

Wanhao Duplicator i3 V2

Parts-list:

-2x M4 Screws to fasten the fan (20mm length should suffice)
-Set of 3D Printed Parts
(depending on your size of mounting bracket: normal for 40mm distance between the screw holes and v2 for 30mm distance, like on the Malyan v2)
-Superglue or any other glue of choice

How do you get this part decently printed when you don't already have a colling fan? Well this is the answer Assembly

This one should be pretty self explanatory.
The small duct piece gets glued to the matching air output on the axial blower, if your part is slightly warped, give it a good pass on some sand paper on a flat surface. while you're at it, you could also true up the fan-output, or just use more glue.

Make sure you orient the piece the right way round!

When the glue has dried, proceed to mounting the Blower to the bracket and the bracket to the printer with the tiny screws from the original fan duct.

Just connect the wiring (you may also want to manage that a little), and you are good to go.

  • Print the two halves with 0.4 mm or less of layer height. Being flat pieces of a certain size, it is necessary a good adhesion to the bed to avoid warping. The hairspray on the glass is not enough.

  • Print the two pieces of the closing mechanism with 0.1 mm of layer height.

  • Glue the largest part of the lock into the corresponding hole in the bottom part box. If you have printed in ABS, use PVC cement.

  • Once dry, place the spring and the opening button, and put a 0.6 mm diameter wire pin in the part of the button protruding into the inside of the box.

  • Put a 0.7 mm diameter wire as a hinge pin.

Extrapolating Tile options S=1" wide, E=2" wide
FI= A curved I (1") with end Openlock connections and Openlock connection on the curve side. Combining 4 walls would make a 2"dia column. As it is a curved, small radius, 1" size matching width to the I series, combining the F and I to create an FI.
FE= Centerline F outside radius. A curved 2" wide tile with end Openlock connections and Openlock connections on curve sides. As it is a curved, small radius, 2" size matching width to the E series, combining the F and E to create an FE.
VE= Centerline V outside radius. A curved 2" wide tile with end Openlock connections and Openlock connections on curve sides. As it is a curved, large radius, 2" size matching width to the E series, combining the V and E to create an VE.

FS= A piece between the H/HS and FI curved tiles with end Openlock connections and Openlock connections on both sides. As is matches an F on the OUTSIDE radius and matching width to the S series, calling it an FS.
HS= An H with end Openlock connections and Openlock connections on both sides. Called an H and matching to the S series to create an HS.
VS= (Previous VS discussion was called X-)A piece between the H/HS and X curved tiles with end Openlock connections and Openlock connections on both sides. As is matches an V on the OUTSIDE radius and matching width to the S series, calling it an VS.

HE= Centerline H outside radius. A curved 2" wide tile with end Openlock connections and Openlock connections on curve sides. As it is a curved, large radius, 2" size matching width to the E series, combining the H and E to create an HE.

XI= A 1" wide X inside radius. Don't know if needed, but included as a possible need.

Also options for different spacing for round hallways on some tiles other than the 4x4 that the standard tiles are based. This will open up for uses in curved roadways, mine track curves and tower options.

This is the second part of a little collection of frame holders for the Prusa I3 MK2 (should fit on the I3 MK1 as well). The collection will at least have the following useful holders:

  1. Filament guide (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2053500)

  4. Camera mount (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2067731)
  5. Filament sensor holder for use with OctoPi

Each of these parts has been designed by different people already and there are many versions available. The idea behind the current collection is to use existing parts where possible and design parts that follow the same design principles (same or similar angles, lengths, same way of mounting to the frame etc.). This gives a much nicer, more homogenous look of the printer.

This LED light holder was once (I think it was designed by gustofusion) on thingiverse and was then deleted. I have completely redesigned the parts, so they comply with my design rules and look similar as compared to the other parts of the collection. description.text: A spool holder with a bearing mounted sleeve that can accommodate larger spools. This replaces the factory spool holder but does not use the factory provided nut.

608ZZ Bearings (5)
1/4 20 threaded rod
1/4 20 Nylock nuts (2)

Assembly

Print all of the parts and clean off excess material.
Insert the bearings into the slots of the Bearing Holder.
Push the threaded rod through the Bearing Holder so that one end is flush with the outside surface of the Bearing Holder on the threaded side (there is a hole cut for the six sided nut, don't insert the nut yet).
Slide the Logo End onto the threaded rod until it mates with the Bearing Holder.
Mark the threaded rod, remove from the assembly and cut to length.
Insert one nut into the keyed hole on the threaded side of the bearing holder (it should fit snuggly).
Insert the threaded rod again into the Bearing Holder this time screw the rod into the nut installed in the previous step.
Slide Sleeve over the Bearing Holder.
Slide the Logo End onto the rod until it mates with the Bearing Holder.
Screw the second nut onto the end of the threaded rod to secure the Logo End. Don't over tighten.
Glue the Logo Cover onto the Logo End. (Optional)
Install on the printer. You will have to rotate the nut in the keyed slot in the printer to insure that the bearings are facing up. Mark the top of the nut so you can install without having to repeat this step should you have to remove the holder.

A spiral stair tread, 30deg/8.4mm tall and 38.1R (3in dia/1.75R)
Wanted to set up a spiral stair that could hold figures. Use as many as you need to get as high as required.

Kudos to Printablescenery
http://www.printablescenery.com/product-category/rampage-system/
Rampage
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1821631
OpenLock 4.0
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1833963
DevonJones
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2034428
Cobble Pattern by Sienna
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1921325

Using Devon Jones Curved wall "cut_stone.wall.TA.1.5rx0.5.curved.openlock" which is a wall made to fit the H floor tile (a 2" inside radius) and the .5inch wall has a 2" outside radius. Created the stair to fit within this open 3in diameter (1.5 in radius).
You would need to use OL2 HE to finish a 8"dia tower floor or 9"dia. with walls.
Here: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2055430

Design: Started with 38.1 dia tread and peg was to be made to fit the "hole". As I made the initial set of treads, I had to print upside down as to not use supports. After printing, realized I could use filament as the peg through the treads. They individually would spin around and I had to glue together to make the picture.
2nd Gen tread had pattern, and I still printed upside down, but used 3.3 hole. Was tight for a 3mm filament as the filament expanded when I used a heat gun with the filament in the "V" of a metal shelving unit leg. Still had to glue. I have changed the tread to have a "key" to set the 60 degree tread to have a 30 degree overlap. Also set the attachment to the round middle support to the outside dia.for greater strength as I broke a few on the bed at that point. (Use the tread end to remove from the bed, not the peg end) Still had to print upside down.
3rd Gen tread had pattern, and supports to allow printing right side up. Still using 3.3 dia hole as the dia is a snug fit for the filament. If you use 1.75dia filament, you can print a 3mm peg, or resize the hole. Also a nail, wood dowel, or other metal support will suffice.
This method used filament for no real good reason.
4th gen had tread pegs and side risers separate and to glue together. Added tabs to locate side risers and treads properly to each other as you build up the stair. Very fiddly, thus rejected.
5th gen. Finally a good all round solution. Set tread to print peg and side risers UP. This allowed one piece treads again, with good fidelity on the stair pattern. No side riser and a spacer peg needed on first tread may not have the best stability for many very heavy figures, but works quite nicely. Top tread needed to have no peg or riser to fit under second floor. Detail obtained was worth it. Tabs in treads space the 60deg treads to 30deg each step which allows a 1" base to fit well on each tread. If you make a very high staircase, the original tread may provide the most stability, (or scale a plain tread with peg and side riser to 5.4mm in z and use that as the base peg and side riser support you may need to stabilize the staircase.)

Spiral Stair Base
Provided all bases plain for your own pattern.Spiral Stair F is round 4" dia (=4x OpenLock "F" tiles clipped together) and Spiral Stair "round" is 3in dia to fit within the Devon Jones walls. As the treads are spaced at 8.4 high, they should (at 5 treads) fit just under the 2nd floor if the floor is set at 50.8mm resting upon the walls. To go higher, just add additional treads. I believe you will have to glue the treads to make it work, although you could always use painters tape on the outside edge to keep the treads together.

"Base" is just a bottom of the stair with a hole for the treads support peg.
"Down" has a clip to allow a fill piece to be added to make it a ground floor "Base", or left out to allow you to go "down".

01/23/17 Updated bases to correct clip size. Added BASE FROUND and DOWN FROUND which is a 3" halfround married to 4" halfround (2xF Tiles)
01/23/17 Added 4x4 U tiles, both BASE and DOWN styles. Took out concept model as it was large and not needed with as built pictures available.
01/25/17 Corrected "math" and clarified notes.
01/27/17 Corrected Treads to match original design size. New treads have supports to print right side up, and tabs for spacing.
2/2/17 Re-thought, why have supports/tabs etc. Why print upside down? Now treads print right side up. Only issue...need to have a different top tread, and a spacer at the bottom. Spacer, 10 cobble treads, 3 tops + plain/top set (for both plain printing or to add your own pattern) and the same plain/top set with a tab with the correct spacing for 30deg treads as shown in the picture. Bottom of tread Tab hole may need cleaning. Spacer can be resized to the height you need to make up any difference you may have in your floor design. Plain top treads or add your own floor design, are now the same tread.
This should complete this design, but still may tweak for ease of use. Typical wall height is 50.8 and you will need spacer first, then 4 treads + 1 top tread to utilize. Tread heights are 8.4. If you use floor supports, add an additional tread in the 180deg stair, by cutting off the tabs and rotate counter clockwise equally to add in the extra tread.

title: Short bowden extruder & E3D v6 bracket for Velleman K8200 / 3Drag

description.text:
Description

An improved bracket for Velleman K8200 / 3Drag to hold E3D v6 hotend (or clones) and generic MK8-based bowden extruder.

Based on Arron_mollet22's idea, designed from scratch in 123D Design.

Use at your own risk. I'm not responsible for misprints, fried stepsticks, your printer catching fire or attacking you. Though this part is working for me.

Improvements

Main improvements (compared to original model)

  • wider parts (8 vs 6 mm for main structures)
  • more accurate dimensions (based on technical drawings of things to be used)
  • better grip on printer's aluminium extrusion/profile
  • added screw for locking hotend in place
  • designed to print without supports and with minimal overhangs

Vitamins needed

  • 4x M4x25 screw (for assembling the bracket)
  • 2x M4x15 screw (for mounting stepper motor bracket)
  • 1x M4x60 screw (for locking the hotend)
  • 7x M4 washer
  • 7x M4 nut

And, of course, you'll need extruder, hotend and a piece of PTFE tubing (about 5cm).

Build notes

  • Push nuts into plastic gently - I've used a vise
  • Don't overtighten the screws
  • Use washers
  • Measure twice (or 4 times), cut once
  • 1mm too much of the tubing won't hurt, it can be squeezed a bit
  • Follow E3D's notes on building the extruder
  • My chinese V6 copy required drilling the pneumatic lock for the tubing to go inside
  • Mount the hotend's fan so that it blows upwards not downwards or it will affect the prints
  • Heater cardridge's and thermistor's cables were long enough so I didn't use original ribbon cable
  • My extruder's spring was too hard so I've removed the additional nut from spring's screw

Usage notes

  • I recommend switching extruder motor driver to DRV8825
  • Increase extruder motor's current to 1.4-1.6A or it will skip
  • I've lost about 2cm of Y-axis movement - might have to reposition the bed or the vertical frame
  • Use PID auto-tuning
  • Add a cover against cold air blows (e.g. pieces of cardboard)

Print settings (for PLA)

  • STEPS_PER_UNIT or STEPS_PER_MM: 100 for original stepstick, 200 for DRV8825
  • Slic3r Print settings: mostly default Slic3r ones, lowered the speeds slightly
  • Slic3r Filament settings:
    • Diameter: 1.75
    • Extrusion multiplier: 1
    • Extruder temperature: 195->190 (depends on your material ofc)
    • Heatbed temperature: 60
    • Cooling: yes (adjust to your needs)
  • Slic3r Printer settings:
    • Extruder nozzle diameter: 0.4

Results

After dealing with problematic heatbed and adding cardboard covers for the printer, it prints nicely.

I've used glass on original heatbed (with additional cardboard insulation below) and stick glue. 0.3 layers, 200% width for first layer.

Still requires some calibration, 3DBenchy pictures included.

title: Replacement retainer ring for Bodum Bistro Coffee Grinder

description.text: This is a replacement part for the Bodum Bistro Electric Burr Coffee Grinder (model 10903).  This is the plastic ring that fits around the burr wheel and joins it to the hopper at the top.  It appears you can order replacement parts for almost everything else in this machine, but not this ring.

This was printed on a Replicator 2 with support and raft and fit with no modification.  Insert the burr wheel into the ring, lock the ring into the grinder, and place the hopper into the opening of the ring.  
This was done in completely parametric OpenSCAD.  It is entirely possible your printer may have different tolerances than mine.  If so and your part doesn't fit, just change the tolerances at the beginning of the scad file and re-render.

This is a set of extended pieces that you can join and make any figure you can imagine.
use it for making shelves for storage, and add more pieces to grow your shelves across a whole wall.

This set includes two sets of "extended pieces" that allow you to grow OUT as wall as Up/Down/Left/Right.
These are good for people with smaller printers who want wider shelves. Like me.

I also included two sets of Ferjerez's original pieces with "extend pieces".
you could mix and match from both to have both curved and straight portions to your shelf creation.

straight from Ferjerez's page:

How it works:

Print a bunch of pieces.
Look for a nice combination
Use pins and glue it to have a strong module
Combine modules
Fix or hook in a wall, put in your desktop or do whatelse you want.
Fill with stuff
Goto 1
The files:

I've include the STL's with the 40x40 mms parts and the pins used for Thingview.
Also included ZIP files with the sets of pieces for 40x40, 40x80,80x40, 80x80,120x40 and 160x40 parts.
Also there's a file with an array of 9 pins. You'll need lots of pins.

About the customizer
If you need a set of parts not included in STL's use the customizer and adapt the sizes of pieces as you needs.

In customizer you set the size of main grid (40mms by default) and the thickness of parts (10 mms default). Then you can generate the parts multipliying grid size by 1 to 4 times.

Important The pins are not enough to make a strong structure. For a strong fix, use pins and apply glue in pins and edge of wallsparts. I'm using instant glue and works really well.

You can use double-sided tape or some hooks or racks to fix the self in walls.

More info...
The pins are 10mm x 5mm. But i'm printing a bit smallers (9 x 4.75). There's no need a perfect fit since i used glue in pins for a good and strong join of parts.

And last...
I'm testing more pieces and parts that can be useful for different designs or funcionallity. Eventually i'll upload some kind of 'expansion pack' with parts compatible with this one.

Hope you find it useful.

Happy printing and have fun!!

A long standing issue with a couple of our FDM machines has been the fact that filament picks up dust or other grime and so jams or at the least results in prints that aren't quite as clean as they could be.

I knocked this together in Fusion 360 and printed it out on our Form 2 so that at some point I can silicone mould and cast it.

The larger part is designed to be stuck using double sided tape to the back of your printer (or wherever works for you). The clip section is held together using four round magnets (4mm diameter and 1.5mm thick) and the clip can then be attached to the base section by two rectangular magnets (6 x 4 x 2 mm). All these magnets were glued in with two part epoxy.

Once you've done that all you need is two small rectangles of foam or sponge to put in the two holder sections, a bit of mineral oil to drop in and you're good to go. No more dust problems and nice, lubricated filament.

Tolerances are currently set a little wide for SLA machines (still work just fine if you're more liberal with the epoxy) but they should be just right for FDM machines to print out

Open in OpenSCAD to change the dimensions of the tube socket.  Once printer, you can either use a hose clamp to clamp the socket tightly around the tube you are using or you can drill holes through the socket and tube you are using to fasten them together with bolts.

comments.text: In case you missed it in the print settings, do not use a raft to print this. It defeats the purpose. That means you may need to make some adjustments to get the piece to adhere to print properly. After it has been installed be sure to adjust your z-axis stop screw BEFORE you home the z-axis. You want it to be longer so the head will stop before it crashes into the bed which will now be higher by the height of this part. This part shows as 3mm high so you need to make that much of an adjustment in the z-axis screw. Play it safe and go a little farther then adjust from there.
